@page "/"


<PageTitle>Snake Game Client Homepage</PageTitle>

<h1>Snake Client – CS 3500 Assignment 9</h1>

<p>
    This project is a networked Snake client built in Blazor that connects
    to the provided Snake server application. The server owns all game logic; this client
    is responsible for rendering the world and sending player input.
</p>

<h2>How to Run</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Start the provided Snake Server application with settings.xml in the same folder.</li>
    <li>If you want ai snakes start the provided AIClient application as well.</li>
    <li>Run the Blazor Snake client from Visual Studio.</li>
    <li>
        In the Snake page:
        <ul>
            <li>Enter your player name.</li>
            <li>Enter the server host (usually localhost) and port (11000 by default).</li>
            <li>Click Connect.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Use WASD or the Arrow keys to control your snake.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Design Overview</h2>

<h3>Models (World, Snake, Wall, PowerUp, Point2D, ControlCommand)</h3>
<ul>
    <li>World: holds the authoritative world state: all snakes, walls, and powerups.</li>
    <li>Snake: mirrors the JSON from the server (ID, name, body, direction, score, alive/died/dc/join flags).</li>
    <li>Wall: represents axis-aligned wall segments and can expand itself into 50×50 blocks.</li>
    <li>PowerUp: represents collectible items, including their “died” state.</li>
    <li>Point2D: is a simple integer (X,Y) world coordinate.</li>
    <li>ControlCommand: sends serialized JSON to the server based on user keyboard clicks.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Networking</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Reuses the NetworkConnection and ServerConnection library from Assignment 8.</li>
    <li>
        The client sends:
        <ul>
            <li>Player name (first line).</li>
            <li>Control commands for movement.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        The client receives:
        <ul>
            <li>Player ID  and world size .</li>
            <li>JSON lines for walls, snakes, and powerups each frame.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li><h4>Disconnect handeling</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>On a requested disconnect (i.e. clicking the button), the screen clears and shows a
                disconnected window in place of the game</li>
             <li>On an irregular disconnect (i.e. a server issue, networking problem, ect), a popup 
                appears and explains what went wrong, confiring that it wasnt the users fault</li>
                <li>A similar popup appears when the user attempts to connect to 
                    an invalid address/port </li>
        </ul>
        </li>

</ul>

<h3>View / Rendering</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Uses Blazor.Extensions.Canvas for a 2D drawing surface.</li>
    <li>A JavaScript animation loop calls back into C# every frame to run Draw.</li>
    <li>The camera is centered on the local player’s snake head using canvas transforms.</li>
    <li>Walls, snakes, and powerups are drawn in world-space; FPS and scoreboard are drawn in screen-space HUD.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Controls & HUD</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Movement: W / A / S / D or Arrow keys.</li>
    <li>
       HUD shows:
        <ul>
            <li>Average FPS.</li>
            <li>A scoreboard with player names and scores, highlighting the local player.</li>
            <li>Player names drawn above each snake in the world.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

